      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that intervention is always a risk is a classic liberal justification for unilateral action, but it ignores the strategic reality of statecraft. Protecting human rights is a moral imperative, but when that imperative leads to the complete dissolution of a nation-state, it becomes a geopolitical disaster. The cost of inaction is measured in immediate atrocities, but the cost of poorly executed intervention is measured in years of regional terrorism and instability.",
      "source": "target",
